Type: The second iteration of Whole Lotta Red represents Carti‚Äôs peak of experimentation, extending his use of the ‚Äúbaby voice‚Äù and high-pitched vocals to new extremes. During this period, he collaborated with Pi‚Äôerre Bourne, Richie Souf, and Art Dealer, performing over a blend of ethereal synth-driven production and hard trap beats. However, following the mixed reception to the single ‚Äú@ MEH,‚Äù Carti abandoned and reworked the project prior to its final release. The cover art associated with this era comes from the ‚Äú@ MEH‚Äù single, marking a transitional phase in his career.  Carti also underwent a significant aesthetic transformation, dyeing his hair blonde, transitioning from freeform dreads to re-twists, and embracing avant-garde fashion, particularly Rick Owens. The upside-down cross became a central motif in his imagery, symbolically tied to his Opium collective. Although divisive at the time, the V2 sound is now widely regarded as a fan favorite, with many of its tracks considered grails, solidifying this as one of the most experimental and influential phases of his career.

Type: Following the death of his friend Bigg Sosa, Carti delayed the release of the album and withdrew from social media until October, when he returned to announce the rollout of his second studio album, Whole Lotta Red. While Carti is not typically recognized for lyrical depth, several tracks address the grief he experienced after Bigg Sosa‚Äôs passing and his methods of coping, most notably on ILoveUIHateU, where he reflects on his struggles with drug addiction. The music from this period adopts a more somber and subdued tone compared to his earlier work, replacing the baby-voice delivery with an early form of his raspy vocal style. This artistic shift was partly a response to the widespread criticism directed at his use of the baby-voice, leading him to explore a darker and more aggressive approach. According to leakers, a September version of Whole Lotta Red existed with a finalized tracklist, although it is unlikely this version will ever be publicly heard.

Type: In late 2020, Carti shifted the sound of Whole Lotta Red into an aggressive ode to punk rock aesthetics, while maintaining the repetitive vocal style that made his previous work so loved. The album was his biggest musical departure by far, forgoing most of the things that brought him success in the first place, such as production from Pi'erre Bourne or features from popular collaborators like Lil Uzi Vert or A$AP Rocky. Instead, the album featured only a handful of guest appearances and production predominantly handled by F1LTHY and Art Dealer. Connecting to V3, Carti uses this album to talk about his acts of violence, expressing how he felt when Bigg Sosa died, moving from grief to anger. On songs like ‚ÄúOn That Time,‚Äù ‚ÄúStop Breathing,‚Äù and ‚ÄúNo Sl33p,‚Äù he opens up about his emotions, displaying anger, sometimes sadness, and vengeance for his friend. Ye served as the executive producer for the album, which was released on Christmas Day, 2020.

Type: In early 2023, anticipation for Playboi Carti‚Äôs next album was through the roof. He had just previewed ‚ÄúROCKSTARZ‚Äù at Rolling Loud California, and it felt like the album could drop any week. Around this time, DJ Swamp Izzo emerged as a trusted insider in the Carti community, sharing key info in DMs with a fan. He claimed Carti had a few possible titles in mind, despite previously teasing the name MUSIC in 2022, and said the official title would drop in two weeks (which never happened). This led to speculation about whether this was a new project, or just MUSIC under a different name. Swamp also mentioned that about 25 tracks were in consideration and hinted at an April or May release. Swamp stated that he would speak over each song, something that later became a main gimmick of MUSIC when it released, and that the sound for the tape was inspired by Lil Wayne, with Carti blending all of his sounds together with a touch of 2000s Atlanta trap. After two grueling years of constant blueballing, Carti finally dropped MUSIC, and once it was out, more details surfaced about the behind-the-scenes process. In an April 2025 interview Swamp Izzo revealed Carti had completed an entire tape by the end of 2022, but no tracks from it made the final tracklist for MUSIC.

Type: After the rollout for the GUAPO era of MUSIC died down, Carti went back into a hiatus. However, this didn‚Äôt last long, as he was booked for multiple festivals across Europe in the summer of 2023. While in Europe, Carti rented out a cave in Paris and recorded various songs there. The songs made during this period were more experimental and unlike the rest of his music. Tracks like POP OUT, MEET YO MAKER, and DOCTOR were all recorded in these caves, with most of the production handled by F1LTHY. Carti eventually moved away from this cave sound and explored a darker theme. The only song from this era (that we know of at least) to see an official release was POP OUT. The cover for this era is fanmade (was originally thought to be real but turns out RunAw lied about the entire thing) & references a Cannibal Corpse album cover.

Type: Playboi Carti's third studio album, MUSIC, was released on March 14, 2025. After a failed rollout in January 2023, Carti revamped the album concept, embracing a darker, gothic, and metal-inspired musical aesthetic. This new sound was driven by gritty beats, mainly produced by Cardo Got Wings, and a mix of deep, menacing vocal delivery with his signature whispery, melodic style. In 2023, Carti largely went silent, resurfacing in July with a feature on Travis Scott's UTOPIA on the track "FE!N," which showcased his newly adopted deep vocal tone. In December 2023, he dropped the first single, "DIFFERENT DAY," followed by "2024," which highlighted both his vocal range and a shift toward sample-based production. Singles like "HBA," "BACKR00MS" with Travis Scott, "EVIL J0RDAN," and "KETAMINE" continued to generate anticipation. He also featured on major projects, including VULTURES 1 and We Don't Trust You, maintaining his presence in the spotlight. The album's release in March 2025 was highly anticipated, marking a significant evolution in Carti's sound. This was also the first time Carti has incorporated AI into his music, using Keith Lawson to record songs for him and run it through a filter to turn it into his voice. Songs like RATHER LIE and FINE SHIT are very clearly AI tracks.

Type: CARTI YE is a collaborative project between Playboi Carti and Kanye West. Little is known of the album, except that sessions for the project took place and it was ultimately scrapped. Kanye posted the album cover on X on March 15, 2025, alongside confirming that the project was discontinued. Later on a stream, F1LTHY would come out and claim that it was actually a track meant for their scrapped collaborative album "CARTI YE".Ye uploading it without Carti was most likely part of the episode he was having at the time, incidently starting a beef with Carti. YoungBoy for his part, decided to stick to Carti's side generating more anticipation for future collaborations.
